<br>
The first thing you're gonna wanna do is discard all your views on reality. 

I can't write something inside of a page without having it break tone, and if I did, the admins are gonna come down from the Heavens and bestow upon me Divine Justice. I don't want that. ''You'' don't want that. Why? Because if someone were to give this page a good ol' rewrite, your existence might be completely different.

I'll get to that later, though.

So, you're wondering what Phenomenon 31 ''actually'' is? Well, I planned on giving a couple hints in the Speculation heading, but I got kinda lazy. Ergo, I just skipped a few lines, came up with something off the top of my head, and ''[[Level 101|boo-gyah]]''! You got what you got, and you got what I wrote (lame rhyme scheme, I know). 

Let me give you a brief introduction to the universe.

Everything you see — everything you can touch, feel, grope, and look at are all interconnected. Not through physics or science, ''but physical sets of mathematics''.  If you're confused: 

About every level stored in the Backrooms are made out of sets of strings and letters. Said strings and letters are all "intertwined" to a collective "backbone" of the universe. At least, that's what I call it (come on, "Backrooms" and "Backbone," gimme a chance).

Phenomenon 31 can't happen alone. It needs a ''user.'' It needs someone to interact with the Backbone. It needs someone to ''interact with the code.'' So, how does it work? Well, there's just this one, big, bright and shiny edit button on the top. And once someone clicks it, boom! Everything changes. Maybe there'll be a rewrite template first, but hey. It'll change.

Obviously, Reformation is hard. To kickstart Phenomenon 31, you need to actually touch the code that makes the page, and I don't know about you, but coding isn't really easy; especially if you're trying to get out a new format.

But once you're done? Ooh boy. You either let the page rest in its new, cutthroat up-to-style theme pertaining to the original, or you go for round 2. Or, you can call in a round 3. Or round 4. Call in multiple rounds, actually. Because people need good pages. They need something to be hooked with — to be ''interested'' with. That's why the Backrooms gained popularity, and that's why Pixels decided to choose it.

Sorry, fourth wall break there. Might not rest well with those reading this page.

Look, point is: you wanna know why levels keep changing? Why your Database is farming more and more pixels? Why there's a hay barrel falling out of the sky, or, Hell, why a bunch of entities and PoIs just suddenly spawned in?

Because someone is editing your article. ''Someone'' is editing your ''page''. For now, that someone is me. But who knows, if the audience doesn't like the concept of this article — if they hate it so much it would make their eyes bleed — then maybe, ''just'' maybe, someone else will take up the pen and write.

What happens after that, I don't know.

But FYI, if a rewrite is happening right in front of you and you can't do anything to stop it, just know that some of you ''might not make it past the final draft''.

Anyways, that's all for now. I've taken up too much time, and I suppose the author credits have to go in somewhere. 

Adieu.




















